WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:09.092
<i>Joyner-Kersee won gold
over Soviet Irina Belova</i>

2
00:00:09.176 --> 00:00:10.737
<i>in last night's race.</i>

3
00:00:10.761 --> 00:00:13.096
<i>And in Houston.
more questions are being asked</i>

4
00:00:13.180 --> 00:00:15.682
<i>in the wake of the Polaris hotel disaster</i>

5
00:00:15.766 --> 00:00:18.810
<i>and the tragic deaths
that occurred in Earth orbit.</i>

6
00:00:18.894 --> 00:00:20.854
<i>NASA has vowed a full investigation</i>

7
00:00:20.938 --> 00:00:23.815
<i>and review
of its safety certification process.</i>

8
00:00:23.899 --> 00:00:26.860
<i>while some in Congress are questioning
NASA's lack of oversight.</i>

9
00:00:26.944 --> 00:00:28.278
Can you please turn that off?

10
00:00:28.362 --> 00:00:30.632
- <i>The tragedy has left the public asking...</i>
- Yes. ma'am.

11
00:01:15.993 --> 00:01:17.619
- Ms. Baldwin.
- Hmm.

12
00:01:18.829 --> 00:01:20.789
Thank you for coming all the way out here.

13
00:01:20.873 --> 00:01:21.874
Sure.

14
00:01:29.631 --> 00:01:32.593
I am... I'm truly sorry about Sam.

15
00:01:33.677 --> 00:01:34.803
Thank you.

16
00:01:34.887 --> 00:01:39.057
You two built something amazing together.

17
00:01:44.396 --> 00:01:45.689
It's why I asked you here.

18
00:02:00.579 --> 00:02:01.556
Is it not enough?

19
00:02:01.580 --> 00:02:04.291
Uh. no. it's very generous.

20
00:02:04.875 --> 00:02:07.169
So... So generous it makes me wonder why.

21
00:02:08.586 --> 00:02:12.090
Our... Our company's reputation is
in tatters.

22
00:02:12.174 --> 00:02:14.676
I mean. our debtors are calling in
their loans.

23
00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:18.281
I mean. if you were gonna
sell Polaris off for parts.

24
00:02:18.305 --> 00:02:20.265
you would make me a lowball offer.

25
00:02:25.354 --> 00:02:27.856
But you are not just in this
for the money.

26
00:02:29.608 --> 00:02:30.609
No.

27
00:02:33.111 --> 00:02:35.447
You know. I read somewhere
you're testing a new methane engine.

28
00:02:36.657 --> 00:02:38.283
From what I know.

29
00:02:38.367 --> 00:02:41.370
methane doesn't offer much advantage
for trips to the moon.

30
00:02:43.247 --> 00:02:44.540
But it does to Mars.

31
00:02:45.874 --> 00:02:48.019
From what I can tell.
Helios doesn't have a ship

32
00:02:48.043 --> 00:02:50.504
that could support a crew
for a two-year trip.

33
00:02:51.588 --> 00:02:54.317
So you must be five years away
from building one.

34
00:02:54.341 --> 00:02:56.903
Seven. actually.

35
00:02:56.927 --> 00:03:01.932
But if you were to acquire a ship
that could support human life.

36
00:03:02.558 --> 00:03:05.912
let's say my hotel.
and attach your new engines to it...

37
00:03:05.936 --> 00:03:08.272
That's a fascinating theory.

38
00:03:16.280 --> 00:03:17.781
You seriously think you can do it?

39
00:03:19.950 --> 00:03:22.995
My dad came to this country
with just a few shillings in his pocket.

40
00:03:24.246 --> 00:03:26.558
And he got a degree
and became an engineer.

41
00:03:26.582 --> 00:03:28.500
He believed what Jack Kennedy said.

42
00:03:28.584 --> 00:03:32.337
"In America... anything is possible."

43
00:03:33.088 --> 00:03:36.216
I can still remember him sitting
in that living room that night in '69.

44
00:03:36.300 --> 00:03:37.968
glued to the TV.

45
00:03:39.136 --> 00:03:42.055
watching the Soviets plant their red flag
on the moon.

46
00:03:42.556 --> 00:03:45.517
The tears were rolling down his cheeks.

47
00:03:46.476 --> 00:03:48.896
I had never even seen him cry before.

48
00:03:50.939 --> 00:03:54.252
Being first. it meant something.

49
00:03:54.276 --> 00:03:56.653
But you are going up against
the two wealthiest.

50
00:03:56.737 --> 00:03:59.239
most powerful nations in the world.

51
00:03:59.323 --> 00:04:02.177
And if they divide up Mars
like they did the moon.

52
00:04:02.201 --> 00:04:06.955
we'll never end this destructive cycle.
This "us... versus them."

53
00:04:08.749 --> 00:04:11.543
In Kenya. there's a Kiswahili word.
"<i>harambee</i>."

54
00:04:12.461 --> 00:04:15.797
It means "stronger together."
Mutual responsibility.

55
00:04:16.757 --> 00:04:21.053
That is what Helios is all about.

56
00:04:22.387 --> 00:04:26.910
That! That's what's gonna push mankind
to make the next leap forward.

57
00:04:26.934 --> 00:04:31.813
Colonizing Mars. and the moons
of... of Saturn and... and Jupiter.

58
00:04:42.783 --> 00:04:44.636
I suppose now your price goes up.

59
00:04:44.660 --> 00:04:47.329
Oh. that was a great speech.

60
00:04:48.288 --> 00:04:50.457
I mean. it was worth at least another 10%.

61
00:04:56.964 --> 00:04:59.716
Okay. Karen Baldwin. Done.

62
00:05:02.719 --> 00:05:04.680
I'll have my lawyers draw up
the paperwork.

63
00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:12.688
Congratulations.

64
00:05:52.561 --> 00:05:57.941
<i>Five. four. three. two. one.</i>

65
00:07:28.615 --> 00:07:30.367
Make a hole. people! Coming through!

66
00:07:46.300 --> 00:07:48.468
I need to see the generalissimo
right fucking now.

67
00:07:48.552 --> 00:07:49.469
She's not available.

68
00:07:49.553 --> 00:07:50.929
- She still in Huntsville?
- Yes.

69
00:07:51.013 --> 00:07:53.116
Well. maybe you can explain
this bullshit to me.

70
00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:57.579
I... I can't. 'cause I don't read. uh...
I don't read braille.

71
00:07:57.603 --> 00:08:02.774
I'll bet you transcribe every word the
mistress of darkness spews from her lair.

72
00:08:02.858 --> 00:08:06.028
What. she think I wouldn't notice
this gem buried at the end?

73
00:08:06.737 --> 00:08:11.384
"Astronaut candidates must conform
to criteria

74
00:08:11.408 --> 00:08:16.681
to be established by the Astronaut
Candidate Qualifications Committee."

75
00:08:16.705 --> 00:08:20.083
Ha! Committee of handpicked stooges.
no doubt.

76
00:08:20.167 --> 00:08:22.437
Of all the backstabbing. underhanded...

77
00:08:22.461 --> 00:08:23.670
You're overreacting.

78
00:08:23.754 --> 00:08:25.690
The committee is merely
an advisory board that's ju...

79
00:08:25.714 --> 00:08:26.798
Bullshit!

80
00:08:26.882 --> 00:08:29.635
This is a power grab. Plain and simple.

81
00:08:30.594 --> 00:08:33.514
- She's trying to force my hand.
- Force your hand?

82
00:08:34.264 --> 00:08:35.640
The Mars mission.

83
00:08:36.517 --> 00:08:38.727
Our fearless leader needs
to remember one thing.

84
00:08:38.809 --> 00:08:41.623
I decide who goes up and when.

85
00:08:41.647 --> 00:08:44.775
no matter what she writes
in any goddamn memo!

86
00:08:45.776 --> 00:08:48.195
Come on. Ollie. Let's go.

87
00:08:51.865 --> 00:08:55.303
Listen. with your getting
doctorates in advanced robotics

88
00:08:55.327 --> 00:08:58.622
and your lunar experience.
I think you are ideally suited

89
00:08:59.122 --> 00:09:01.416
to command the Mars '98 mission.

90
00:09:06.713 --> 00:09:08.382
The second mission to Mars.

91
00:09:09.925 --> 00:09:11.319
So let me get this straight.

92
00:09:11.343 --> 00:09:14.721
My advanced qualifications actually
worked against me going first?

93
00:09:16.139 --> 00:09:18.058
Well. yeah. They kinda did.

94
00:09:20.269 --> 00:09:22.437
I don't suppose the fact
that you and Ed go way back...

95
00:09:22.521 --> 00:09:25.440
Oh. don't go there. Dani.
You... You and I go just as far.

96
00:09:25.941 --> 00:09:26.984
I know.

97
00:09:28.068 --> 00:09:29.736
But you're wrong on this one. Molly.

98
00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:33.156
Well. it's my call.
and that's how I see it.

99
00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:36.910
Yeah. there's no argument
you'd be better at handling the science.

100
00:09:36.994 --> 00:09:39.389
Someone with your qualifications
will be invaluable

101
00:09:39.413 --> 00:09:41.349
once the first flight's proven
it can be done

102
00:09:41.373 --> 00:09:44.686
and we start building the infrastructure
for a permanent base.

103
00:09:44.710 --> 00:09:48.046
But Ed is first. last
and always a test pilot.

104
00:09:48.130 --> 00:09:50.090
And he's used to handling the unknown.

105
00:09:50.174 --> 00:09:51.568
And a first flight to Mars...

106
00:09:51.592 --> 00:09:53.677
...is full of huge unknowns.

107
00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:59.117
He might not be the guy
who's gonna find life on Mars.

108
00:09:59.141 --> 00:10:03.413
But he is the guy who. I think. has the
best chance of getting the mission done

109
00:10:03.437 --> 00:10:05.772
and bringing everyone home alive.

110
00:10:10.527 --> 00:10:11.653
This sucks.

111
00:10:14.072 --> 00:10:15.383
Yeah. it does.

112
00:10:16.575 --> 00:10:20.555
And I-I totally understand
if you don't wanna lead his backup crew.

113
00:10:20.579 --> 00:10:22.372
So you think about that. you let me know.

114
00:10:22.456 --> 00:10:24.958
I don't need to think about it.

115
00:10:25.042 --> 00:10:26.376
I'll back him up.

116
00:10:27.169 --> 00:10:30.464
Whatever the program needs.
whatever Ed needs.

117
00:10:32.049 --> 00:10:33.050
I'll be there.

118
00:10:36.386 --> 00:10:41.099
Now. as you can see.
we can make methane. hydrogen and oxygen

119
00:10:41.183 --> 00:10:44.204
from the atmosphere
and water resources on Mars.

120
00:10:44.228 --> 00:10:47.457
Now. the question I pose to you is

121
00:10:47.481 --> 00:10:51.628
which technology offers the best trade-off
for a long-duration Mars mission

122
00:10:51.652 --> 00:10:53.362
with the goals we discussed?

123
00:11:00.619 --> 00:11:03.330
Now. remember. it's not just about mass.

124
00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:07.769
Keep in mind the power requirements
for liquification. transportation

125
00:11:07.793 --> 00:11:09.896
and storage in each case.

126
00:11:09.920 --> 00:11:12.297
D-mail your analyses to me
by next Wednesday.

127
00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:16.927
Belay that. children.
You can submit your work to Ken Muriata.

128
00:11:17.511 --> 00:11:19.948
He will be taking over this class
from now on.

129
00:11:19.972 --> 00:11:21.032
Why?

130
00:11:21.056 --> 00:11:22.492
Wasn't my call.

131
00:11:22.516 --> 00:11:26.788
The Astronaut Candidate
Qualification Committee has concerns

132
00:11:26.812 --> 00:11:31.316
about your availability
for the next couple of years.

133
00:11:37.406 --> 00:11:38.550
Don't fuck with me. Molly.

134
00:11:38.574 --> 00:11:40.909
Now. why would I do that. Admiral?

135
00:11:41.910 --> 00:11:44.037
Because you're drunk with power.

136
00:11:45.372 --> 00:11:47.040
I never should've given you that job.

137
00:11:48.208 --> 00:11:51.211
Well.
we all make decisions we regret.

138
00:11:52.337 --> 00:11:54.965
I hope this doesn't turn out
to be one of mine.

139
00:11:59.595 --> 00:12:00.596
Seriously?

140
00:12:02.472 --> 00:12:03.473
That's right.

141
00:12:05.142 --> 00:12:08.997
Edward Baldwin is gonna command
America's first mission to Mars.

142
00:12:16.111 --> 00:12:17.487
Holy shit.

143
00:12:19.031 --> 00:12:20.657
Holy shit!

144
00:12:27.122 --> 00:12:30.250
- Do not fuck this up.
- Fuck this up.

145
00:13:17.798 --> 00:13:18.799
Hey there.

146
00:13:19.758 --> 00:13:22.529
Danny! What are you doing here?

147
00:13:22.553 --> 00:13:26.181
Ah. Came to pick up Mom's astronaut pin
from Sam's office.

148
00:13:31.228 --> 00:13:32.688
I remember the day that she got that.

149
00:13:33.939 --> 00:13:37.484
Sam was always so proud of your mom.
You know that?

150
00:13:39.403 --> 00:13:40.612
He was proud of you too.

151
00:13:42.406 --> 00:13:45.742
Way you pulled your life together
after everything.

152
00:13:45.826 --> 00:13:47.119
It's really great.

153
00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:52.392
Glad you were able to sell the company.

154
00:13:52.416 --> 00:13:54.209
At least you're walking away
with some money.

155
00:13:54.293 --> 00:13:55.544
Well. that's thanks to you.

156
00:13:56.545 --> 00:13:59.149
If you hadn't have turned off
that thruster. I...

157
00:13:59.173 --> 00:14:00.966
I wouldn't even be standing here.

158
00:14:01.675 --> 00:14:05.697
Eh. it wasn't completely altruistic.
Saved my own ass too.

159
00:14:07.556 --> 00:14:10.601
Uh. guess I better get going.

160
00:14:15.689 --> 00:14:16.690
Hey. Danny?

161
00:14:19.526 --> 00:14:22.362
At the reception...

162
00:14:24.948 --> 00:14:26.533
w-why did you play it?

163
00:14:27.075 --> 00:14:28.076
Play what?

164
00:14:29.745 --> 00:14:30.954
That song.

165
00:14:33.373 --> 00:14:34.374
Oh.

166
00:14:36.084 --> 00:14:37.503
It was Amber's idea.

167
00:14:38.795 --> 00:14:40.214
She's a Billy Swan fan too.

168
00:14:44.635 --> 00:14:46.738
Well. it's a great song.

169
00:14:46.762 --> 00:14:47.846
Yeah.

170
00:14:49.723 --> 00:14:50.724
Good night.

171
00:14:59.775 --> 00:15:01.878
- Karen?
- Yeah?

172
00:15:01.902 --> 00:15:03.445
I lied just then.

173
00:15:04.363 --> 00:15:08.176
About the song. About you and me.

174
00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:10.536
- About everything. Look. just listen.
- Danny...

175
00:15:11.578 --> 00:15:14.665
Okay. the day of the wedding.
I felt sick to my stomach.

176
00:15:16.041 --> 00:15:17.352
I didn't know exactly what it was

177
00:15:17.376 --> 00:15:20.337
until I was out there
with the world spinning below me. but...

178
00:15:21.922 --> 00:15:23.465
in that moment.
I wasn't thinking about Amber.

179
00:15:23.549 --> 00:15:25.652
- I don't want to hear this.
- All I was thinking about was you.

180
00:15:25.676 --> 00:15:27.135
- That's not okay.
- It's the truth.

181
00:15:27.219 --> 00:15:29.322
- I don't care. I don't wanna hear it.
- I thought about your eyes.

182
00:15:29.346 --> 00:15:31.306
- What? Oh. my God.
- The smell of your hair. your lips.

183
00:15:31.390 --> 00:15:33.433
- Go. Get out of here.
- How I might never see you again.

184
00:15:33.517 --> 00:15:36.562
Hey! Stop it. right now. Stop it!

185
00:15:39.064 --> 00:15:40.649
That's enough!

186
00:15:41.233 --> 00:15:44.862
Jesus. I thought that
you moved beyond all of this!

187
00:15:46.989 --> 00:15:47.990
I tried.

188
00:15:49.449 --> 00:15:51.261
You... You don't know how hard I tried.

189
00:15:51.285 --> 00:15:53.054
Okay. well.
I'm not going through it again.

190
00:15:53.078 --> 00:15:56.206
You're not gonna start calling me
in the middle of the night again

191
00:15:56.290 --> 00:15:58.208
and showing up at my house drunk.

192
00:15:58.292 --> 00:15:59.960
It's not gonna happen. okay?

193
00:16:01.962 --> 00:16:04.089
You have to move on.

194
00:16:05.007 --> 00:16:06.008
Please.

195
00:16:07.092 --> 00:16:10.262
It was a mistake. okay? I'm... I'm sorry.

196
00:16:11.138 --> 00:16:13.015
It never should have happened.

197
00:16:18.103 --> 00:16:19.438
Is it because of Ed?

198
00:16:20.189 --> 00:16:21.190
What?

199
00:16:21.982 --> 00:16:23.960
I saw the way you both were
at the wedding.

200
00:16:23.984 --> 00:16:26.129
I can't believe you're gonna
get back with that son of a bitch.

201
00:16:26.153 --> 00:16:27.714
Oh. my God. Danny.

202
00:16:27.738 --> 00:16:29.948
The way he talks down to you. to everyone.

203
00:16:30.032 --> 00:16:32.075
like he's God's gift to this world
or something.

204
00:16:32.159 --> 00:16:34.679
Danny. this has nothing to do with Ed.

205
00:16:34.703 --> 00:16:36.205
Nothing! Okay?

206
00:16:36.705 --> 00:16:39.333
Y-You... You need to go home to your wife.

207
00:17:07.736 --> 00:17:09.154
But I like John.

208
00:17:09.988 --> 00:17:13.510
He and I see eye to eye on most issues.
and we have a great rapport.

209
00:17:13.534 --> 00:17:15.178
It's not about rapport.

210
00:17:15.202 --> 00:17:18.890
It's about choosing a vice president
that'll add value to the ticket.

211
00:17:18.914 --> 00:17:20.540
Picking a moderate like McCain...

212
00:17:20.624 --> 00:17:22.835
Will help me attract Democrats.

213
00:17:23.710 --> 00:17:26.481
He favors lower taxes and spending.
and less regulation.

214
00:17:26.505 --> 00:17:29.842
but he's also pretty socially liberal
and a war hero.

215
00:17:30.676 --> 00:17:33.238
If something happened to me.
he'd make a great president.

216
00:17:33.262 --> 00:17:35.472
Well. we wouldn't really need
to worry about that

217
00:17:35.556 --> 00:17:37.724
if you don't become president
in the first place.

218
00:17:39.977 --> 00:17:41.603
You don't need another you.

219
00:17:41.687 --> 00:17:44.624
You need someone
who will shore up your weaknesses.

220
00:17:44.648 --> 00:17:46.334
Clinton's up by six in most polls.

221
00:17:46.358 --> 00:17:48.795
and he's got a 20-point edge
with male voters.

222
00:17:48.819 --> 00:17:51.321
Yeah. it doesn't matter
that I'm a former astronaut

223
00:17:51.405 --> 00:17:53.615
who put my life on the line
for over a decade.

224
00:17:54.324 --> 00:17:57.327
I'm running in a party
that's infatuated with alpha males.

225
00:17:57.411 --> 00:18:00.330
so I need one on the ticket. Is that it?

226
00:18:00.414 --> 00:18:03.584
Exactly. Preferably someone
who will excite the evangelicals.

227
00:18:05.335 --> 00:18:08.172
That's why I want you
to give another look at Bragg.

228
00:18:09.423 --> 00:18:11.985
It doesn't have to be someone you like.

229
00:18:12.009 --> 00:18:14.011
It has to be someone the base likes.

230
00:18:14.761 --> 00:18:17.157
You know what he said about Mars?

231
00:18:17.181 --> 00:18:18.825
He's in favor of a manned mission.

232
00:18:18.849 --> 00:18:21.995
Because. he says.
Mars is in the same orbit as Earth

233
00:18:22.019 --> 00:18:24.271
and has canals full of water.

234
00:18:26.064 --> 00:18:28.960
Okay. he's a little fuzzy on the science.
You'll bring him up to speed.

235
00:18:28.984 --> 00:18:33.488
The... The point is. he's a founding member
of the Conservatives for Jesus Christ.

236
00:18:33.572 --> 00:18:34.573
Yeah.

237
00:18:36.742 --> 00:18:39.077
Are we sure we want someone that far right
on the ticket?

238
00:18:40.704 --> 00:18:43.498
It's not about what we want.
It's about what we need.

239
00:18:48.837 --> 00:18:53.008
Okay. Set up a meeting.
but I am not making any promises.

240
00:18:55.469 --> 00:18:57.429
- Daddy!
- Oh. geez!

241
00:18:59.473 --> 00:19:00.742
Evil hand! Evil hand!

242
00:19:00.766 --> 00:19:04.436
Evil hand. you know. I haven't seen him.
I-I think the coast is clear.

243
00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:06.581
Look out. Daddy!

244
00:19:06.605 --> 00:19:09.918
- Oh. geez! Oh. oh. he's coming for ya!
- Mommy! Help. Mommy!

245
00:19:09.942 --> 00:19:12.569
Get back. evil hand! Get back.

246
00:19:12.653 --> 00:19:15.590
- Whoa! There it comes over here.
- Get back. evil hand!

247
00:19:15.614 --> 00:19:17.157
- Other side.
- Uh-oh. Uh-oh.

248
00:19:17.241 --> 00:19:19.117
- Uh-oh. Oh!
- Bow! Bow!

249
00:19:19.201 --> 00:19:21.054
- Bow! Bow!
- Yeah. Scotty!

250
00:19:22.371 --> 00:19:25.016
You did it! The victor!

251
00:19:36.969 --> 00:19:39.429
- Way to go. Admiral.
- Thanks.

252
00:19:41.598 --> 00:19:42.683
Hi. Bob.

253
00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:46.311
Hi. Bob.

254
00:19:50.190 --> 00:19:52.150
Hope that thing doesn't
slow you down too much.

255
00:19:52.234 --> 00:19:55.153
Nah. Just can't drive a clutch
for a few weeks.

256
00:19:55.237 --> 00:19:56.238
Mmm.

257
00:19:58.323 --> 00:20:02.053
I-I rented one of those new. uh.
electric roadsters.

258
00:20:02.077 --> 00:20:04.329
No gears. Just raw power.

259
00:20:05.080 --> 00:20:08.125
Does zero to 60 in 3.4 seconds.

260
00:20:09.251 --> 00:20:10.252
Sweet!

261
00:20:13.964 --> 00:20:15.424
Congratulations on Mars.

262
00:20:16.425 --> 00:20:18.862
Looks like NASA still values age
over beauty.

263
00:20:18.886 --> 00:20:22.240
Hell no! This assignment cost me
a whole case of Glenfiddich.

264
00:20:22.264 --> 00:20:24.117
You know. Molly. she don't sway easy.

265
00:20:24.141 --> 00:20:26.226
- Don't I know it.
- Look. I promise you.

266
00:20:26.310 --> 00:20:30.832
I'll leave a whole crate of whatever
libation you fancy up there on Mars.

267
00:20:30.856 --> 00:20:35.110
Just so long as that geriatric cadaver
of yours doesn't wither away first.

268
00:20:35.194 --> 00:20:40.258
There is zero chance of that.
Everything is still rock solid.

269
00:20:40.282 --> 00:20:41.658
Except that leg.

270
00:20:41.742 --> 00:20:43.035
It'll heal soon enough.

271
00:20:44.119 --> 00:20:45.120
I hope so.

272
00:20:46.705 --> 00:20:51.043
Because if you stumble.
even for just one second.

273
00:20:52.377 --> 00:20:55.297
I'm gonna swoop in
and steal your seat in a heartbeat.

274
00:20:56.507 --> 00:20:58.967
Me and my backup crew are gonna be
breathing down your neck

275
00:20:59.051 --> 00:21:00.487
all the way to launch.

276
00:21:00.511 --> 00:21:02.846
I expect nothing less.

277
00:21:06.975 --> 00:21:08.936
Come on. Come on.

278
00:21:24.952 --> 00:21:27.162
Hey. Dad. How's your leg?

279
00:21:27.246 --> 00:21:32.227
<i>It's fine. Which you'd know
if you ever returned my calls.</i>

280
00:21:32.251 --> 00:21:33.710
I know. I'm sorry.

281
00:21:34.211 --> 00:21:36.523
<i>Anyways. I-I got some news for you.</i>

282
00:21:36.547 --> 00:21:39.132
Don't tell me.
Yvonne cracked up another car?

283
00:21:41.093 --> 00:21:42.594
<i>No. Um...</i>

284
00:21:44.471 --> 00:21:45.806
<i>You might as well know.</i>

285
00:21:46.431 --> 00:21:49.786
<i>Uh. she and I have...
We're... We're splitting up.</i>

286
00:21:49.810 --> 00:21:55.148
Wow. Less than a year.
That's a new record for you.

287
00:21:55.232 --> 00:21:57.919
<i>You could at least pretend
to be sad about it.</i>

288
00:21:57.943 --> 00:22:00.112
You're right. I'm sorry. That was mean.

289
00:22:01.154 --> 00:22:03.740
So. where are you moving now?

290
00:22:04.241 --> 00:22:06.201
Not back to the Shamrock. I hope.

291
00:22:06.285 --> 00:22:11.206
<i>No. I actually found
a great new neighborhood.</i>

292
00:22:11.290 --> 00:22:12.934
<i>Uh. I think you'll love it.</i>

293
00:22:12.958 --> 00:22:14.585
Really? Where?

294
00:22:18.964 --> 00:22:21.800
In this area right here.

295
00:22:22.551 --> 00:22:24.261
You got the mission?

296
00:22:24.761 --> 00:22:27.556
Holy shit!

297
00:22:29.183 --> 00:22:31.244
Congrats. Dad!

298
00:22:31.268 --> 00:22:33.645
<i>Yeah. I got it.</i>

299
00:22:33.729 --> 00:22:37.065
<i>And word is the Russian engine's got
some serious teething problems.</i>

300
00:22:37.149 --> 00:22:41.445
so. you bet your ass
the US of A's gonna win this race.

301
00:22:42.446 --> 00:22:44.990
<i>And. uh. here's a kicker.</i>

302
00:22:47.743 --> 00:22:48.994
How'd you like to come with me?

303
00:22:50.454 --> 00:22:51.538
Where. to Mars?

304
00:22:51.622 --> 00:22:54.333
<i>You've been preparing for this
your whole life. Kel.</i>

305
00:22:55.042 --> 00:22:59.087
Uh... Would NASA ever risk letting a family
fly together on a mission like this?

306
00:22:59.171 --> 00:23:02.150
Well. your old man's still got some pull
at the office.

307
00:23:02.174 --> 00:23:03.842
Me and Molly got an understanding.

308
00:23:03.926 --> 00:23:05.552
Yeah. the geezer network.

309
00:23:05.636 --> 00:23:08.490
<i>This is a chance for you
to get your head out of the snow. kiddo.</i>

310
00:23:08.514 --> 00:23:10.098
<i>and back into the sky.</i>

311
00:23:11.058 --> 00:23:12.684
<i>I don't know. I...</i>

312
00:23:12.768 --> 00:23:16.706
<i>I'd have to put my research down here
on hold for four. maybe five years.</i>

313
00:23:16.730 --> 00:23:20.400
I offer you a chance to be
one of the first humans on Mars.

314
00:23:20.484 --> 00:23:22.295
and you're talking about research?

315
00:23:22.319 --> 00:23:24.589
<i>I-I-I just don't get it.</i>

316
00:23:24.613 --> 00:23:27.509
<i>Four years of Annapolis.
two years of flight school.</i>

317
00:23:27.533 --> 00:23:31.161
<i>You aced your astronaut training
and your first trip to Skylab.</i>

318
00:23:31.245 --> 00:23:33.997
But instead of going back to space.

319
00:23:34.081 --> 00:23:37.811
you're chasing bacteria
in the ass-end of the world.

320
00:23:37.835 --> 00:23:42.506
This research is teaching us
how life might have evolved on Mars.

321
00:23:43.382 --> 00:23:45.425
We found a strain
of <i>Sphingomonas dessicabilus</i>

322
00:23:45.509 --> 00:23:47.761
that could survive
the extreme cold up there.

323
00:23:47.845 --> 00:23:51.181
<i>So come with me.
bring some swing-a-lings with you.</i>

324
00:23:51.265 --> 00:23:53.767
<i>and figure out
how to grow some shit up there.</i>

325
00:23:53.851 --> 00:23:54.893
<i>Sphingomonas</i>.

326
00:23:56.103 --> 00:23:58.897
<i>S-S-Swingabangas. That's what I said.</i>

327
00:24:01.859 --> 00:24:02.860
So...

328
00:24:03.569 --> 00:24:06.405
Are you in?

329
00:24:08.949 --> 00:24:10.492
Of course I'm in.

330
00:24:12.703 --> 00:24:15.789
<i>Attagirl!
It... It'll be just like old times.</i>

331
00:24:15.873 --> 00:24:18.500
I love you. Always.

332
00:24:19.251 --> 00:24:22.045
Love you too. Dad. Always.

333
00:24:22.129 --> 00:24:23.630
Bye.

334
00:24:35.601 --> 00:24:37.477
- Hey.
- Hey.

335
00:24:40.022 --> 00:24:44.610
Mmm. mmm!
That scampi sure does smell good.

336
00:24:47.070 --> 00:24:48.989
Just be careful
you don't overcook that shrimp.

337
00:24:49.489 --> 00:24:51.384
A good commander
doesn't micromanage her crew.

338
00:24:59.875 --> 00:25:01.502
Guess that's why I didn't get the mission.

339
00:25:04.046 --> 00:25:05.255
Molly gave Mars to Ed.

340
00:25:06.632 --> 00:25:07.758
I'm his backup.

341
00:25:09.092 --> 00:25:10.385
Oh. baby. I'm so sorry.

342
00:25:12.304 --> 00:25:13.722
I know how much you wanted it.

343
00:25:23.857 --> 00:25:25.943
You don't seem
all that broken up about it.

344
00:25:31.740 --> 00:25:32.741
Well...

345
00:25:34.826 --> 00:25:36.787
I gotta admit I am kind of relieved.

346
00:25:38.372 --> 00:25:40.016
I thought you were okay about me going.

347
00:25:40.040 --> 00:25:42.751
Look. I knew space was dangerous.
But it was kind of...

348
00:25:43.877 --> 00:25:46.964
...a-an abstraction. You know?

349
00:25:48.924 --> 00:25:50.884
After what we went through up there.

350
00:25:51.593 --> 00:25:55.639
I know. I... It's real now. I get it.

351
00:25:56.640 --> 00:25:59.536
But I am still slated to go up in 1998.
You know that.

352
00:25:59.560 --> 00:26:00.644
I know.

353
00:26:02.104 --> 00:26:06.024
But at least Isaiah will be out of school.
and he could use all the help he can get.

354
00:26:06.108 --> 00:26:08.086
I don't need help.

355
00:26:08.110 --> 00:26:09.796
Your midterms would suggest otherwise.

356
00:26:09.820 --> 00:26:12.215
You know I like to come from behind.
I'm on it.

357
00:26:12.239 --> 00:26:13.550
Was studying just now.

358
00:26:13.574 --> 00:26:15.927
Is that why I heard all that
simulated gunfire from your room?

359
00:26:17.411 --> 00:26:21.039
So. um. why are we talking
about you being home?

360
00:26:22.708 --> 00:26:25.335
Mr. Baldwin was selected
for the Mars mission.

361
00:26:25.419 --> 00:26:28.255
They picked the old white guy. Shocker.

362
00:26:28.922 --> 00:26:31.341
He gonna take a walker and colostomy bag
up with him?

363
00:26:31.425 --> 00:26:32.759
Okay. come on now.

364
00:26:33.677 --> 00:26:38.473
Hey. the good news is I will be around to
help you out with that AP history paper.

365
00:26:38.557 --> 00:26:39.641
What's the subject again?

366
00:26:39.725 --> 00:26:41.643
- Uh. John Adams.
- Mmm. Mm-hmm.

367
00:26:41.727 --> 00:26:45.123
John Adams. stuffing the courts
with Federalist judges.

368
00:26:45.147 --> 00:26:49.484
The age-old issue.
States' rights versus big government.

369
00:26:49.568 --> 00:26:53.256
Ellen Wilson and Bill Clinton are having
that exact argument today.

370
00:26:53.280 --> 00:26:54.781
Ooh. this is going to be so fun.

371
00:26:54.865 --> 00:26:57.075
Now I really wish you got
that commander job.

372
00:27:01.121 --> 00:27:03.266
<i>Careless spending led
Governor Bill Clinton</i>

373
00:27:03.290 --> 00:27:06.418
<i>to increase the sales tax in Arkansas
by 33%.</i>

374
00:27:07.961 --> 00:27:10.088
<i>And now he's hoping to become president</i>

375
00:27:10.172 --> 00:27:14.194
<i>so he can increase the Federal
government's spending by $220 billion.</i>

376
00:27:14.218 --> 00:27:17.387
<i>forcing every American to pay more taxes.</i>

377
00:27:17.471 --> 00:27:20.200
<i>This is why we need a true American hero
to fight for us.</i>

378
00:27:20.224 --> 00:27:23.036
<i>Senator Ellen Wilson will just say no</i>

379
00:27:23.060 --> 00:27:25.705
<i>to Clinton's disastrous
tax-and-spend policies.</i>

380
00:27:25.729 --> 00:27:27.707
<i>And that's why I'm running for president.</i>

381
00:27:27.731 --> 00:27:30.943
<i>Let's build a better future. Together.</i>

382
00:27:32.110 --> 00:27:35.173
<i>When your favorite pan
is a great grimy mess.</i>

383
00:27:35.197 --> 00:27:37.008
<i>try our new lemon-scented
degreasing formula.</i>

384
00:27:37.032 --> 00:27:38.700
Very excited to have you here. sir.

385
00:27:39.284 --> 00:27:42.287
Governor Bragg.
Thank you for coming on such short notice.

386
00:27:42.371 --> 00:27:43.997
I'm sure you have a lot on your plate.

387
00:27:44.081 --> 00:27:47.125
Well. somehow. I'm guessing
not as much as you. ma'am.

388
00:27:47.209 --> 00:27:48.478
Honored to be here.

389
00:27:48.502 --> 00:27:49.896
Sorry about all the mess.

390
00:27:49.920 --> 00:27:52.297
We're in the process
of moving our campaign headquarters

391
00:27:52.381 --> 00:27:55.884
to a larger building.
and it's been a bit chaotic.

392
00:27:55.968 --> 00:27:57.469
Oh. believe me. I understand.

393
00:27:57.553 --> 00:28:00.430
We just had the Governor's Mansion
renovated last year.

394
00:28:00.514 --> 00:28:03.892
and I am still trying to find
my favorite pair of cuff links.

395
00:28:06.353 --> 00:28:11.191
Well. uh. we haven't had much
in the way of personal interaction.

396
00:28:11.275 --> 00:28:15.195
but I've always admired the
straightforward way you carry yourself.

397
00:28:15.696 --> 00:28:17.507
I like to think we have that in common.

398
00:28:17.531 --> 00:28:19.092
I couldn't agree more.

399
00:28:19.116 --> 00:28:22.494
I have been a fan of yours ever since...

400
00:28:22.578 --> 00:28:24.556
Well. you know.

401
00:28:24.580 --> 00:28:26.683
- The tank?
- The tank.

402
00:28:26.707 --> 00:28:29.853
Heck. that was something.
I'm sure you hear that a lot.

403
00:28:29.877 --> 00:28:32.337
Only every day.

404
00:28:32.421 --> 00:28:35.275
Well. I've been keeping an eye on you
ever since.

405
00:28:35.299 --> 00:28:39.571
and your voice in the Senate has been
so valuable to the party.

406
00:28:39.595 --> 00:28:42.157
You're bringing us into the 21st century.

407
00:28:42.181 --> 00:28:44.516
Kicking and screaming. to be sure.

408
00:28:45.893 --> 00:28:47.102
Thank you for saying that.

409
00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:50.957
So. as I'm sure Larry made you aware.

410
00:28:50.981 --> 00:28:53.692
I'm considering my options
for a running mate.

411
00:28:54.318 --> 00:28:56.069
And before I make my final choice.

412
00:28:56.153 --> 00:28:59.531
I wanted to have a frank conversation
with you.

413
00:28:59.615 --> 00:29:02.117
- Only kind worth having.
- Good.

414
00:29:02.201 --> 00:29:07.080
There are several areas
where you and I don't see eye to eye.

415
00:29:07.873 --> 00:29:09.684
Stem cell research. for example.

416
00:29:09.708 --> 00:29:13.754
True. I do not support stem cell research.

417
00:29:14.254 --> 00:29:16.089
I am staunchly pro-life.

418
00:29:16.173 --> 00:29:17.317
As am I.

419
00:29:17.341 --> 00:29:22.596
but this is a promising area of
scientific research that could save lives.

420
00:29:27.100 --> 00:29:30.437
Look. I want my vice president
to be someone I can rely on

421
00:29:30.521 --> 00:29:33.583
for their honest. unvarnished opinion.

422
00:29:33.607 --> 00:29:34.691
Always.

423
00:29:34.775 --> 00:29:37.444
But I also need that person
to be on the same team.

424
00:29:37.528 --> 00:29:41.323
even if they don't agree with every
decision I make or every position I hold.

425
00:29:42.908 --> 00:29:45.011
There will be times
when I call on my vice president

426
00:29:45.035 --> 00:29:47.829
to advocate for something
they don't agree with.

427
00:29:49.873 --> 00:29:51.834
Is this something you feel
you could handle. Governor?

428
00:29:55.671 --> 00:29:59.258
Are there sacrifices that have to be made?
Of course.

429
00:30:00.133 --> 00:30:03.488
But sacrifice is a part of any journey.

430
00:30:03.512 --> 00:30:06.431
Ma'am. I'm going to be straight with you.
as you've been with me.

431
00:30:06.515 --> 00:30:10.227
There is no one
I would rather be following into a fray

432
00:30:10.727 --> 00:30:13.105
than a true American hero like yourself.

433
00:30:13.730 --> 00:30:17.961
It has been too long
that the Republican Party has been defined

434
00:30:17.985 --> 00:30:19.778
by people that look like me.

435
00:30:21.405 --> 00:30:25.409
I would be honored
if asked to serve with you.

436
00:30:37.421 --> 00:30:39.506
- Hey. You're back early.
- Hey. Mm-hmm.

437
00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:41.693
The electromagnetic containment guys
have the goods?

438
00:30:41.717 --> 00:30:43.111
It's very promising.

439
00:30:43.135 --> 00:30:47.222
Great. I-I... You know. I gotta say.
I'm a little annoyed.

440
00:30:47.764 --> 00:30:48.765
Why?

441
00:30:48.849 --> 00:30:49.951
Well...

442
00:30:49.975 --> 00:30:54.229
Uh. I had a double sawbuck on Danielle
to command Mars '96.

443
00:30:54.313 --> 00:30:55.582
Thought it was a sure thing.

444
00:30:55.606 --> 00:30:59.484
I mean. don't get me wrong.
I understand why you went with Ed. but...

445
00:30:59.568 --> 00:31:01.361
Wait. wait. What did you say?

446
00:31:02.362 --> 00:31:04.448
Uh... Uh... No. just...

447
00:31:05.574 --> 00:31:08.952
I mean. you're picking Ed for commander.

448
00:31:16.627 --> 00:31:17.628
Right?

449
00:31:19.755 --> 00:31:22.090
<i>Personality traits must be altered.</i>

450
00:31:22.174 --> 00:31:26.261
<i>which means Babe Ruth will be stuck with
what the organization initially selected.</i>

451
00:31:28.472 --> 00:31:29.723
Easy. Ollie.

452
00:31:31.266 --> 00:31:34.978
Can you tell me why I have to hear
that you picked Ed Baldwin as commander

453
00:31:35.062 --> 00:31:36.396
from Bill Strausser?

454
00:31:36.480 --> 00:31:38.690
Well. I put it in a memo.

455
00:31:38.774 --> 00:31:41.211
I guess you didn't have a chance
to read mine yet.

456
00:31:41.235 --> 00:31:44.279
We agreed to continue discussing it
when I returned.

457
00:31:44.363 --> 00:31:47.616
Mm-hmm. Here you are.
and here we are discussing it.

458
00:31:48.659 --> 00:31:51.703
Oh. come on. You went behind my back
when I was out of town.

459
00:31:51.787 --> 00:31:52.996
Behind your back?

460
00:31:53.080 --> 00:31:55.892
You mean like putting together a
bogus committee for selecting the ASCANs?

461
00:31:55.916 --> 00:31:58.770
Those are some of the finest
scientific minds at this agency.

462
00:31:58.794 --> 00:32:01.880
Oh. come on. You are trying
to cut the balls off this office

463
00:32:01.964 --> 00:32:05.360
just like you have every other department
in this entire agency

464
00:32:05.384 --> 00:32:07.070
over the last ten years.

465
00:32:07.094 --> 00:32:08.595
That's what you think I'm doing?

466
00:32:08.679 --> 00:32:13.308
You don't like having someone around
who doesn't kowtow to your every whim.

467
00:32:14.101 --> 00:32:17.604
I don't care how many friends you got
in Washington.

468
00:32:17.688 --> 00:32:20.333
- I will not allow you to steamroll...
- Allow?

469
00:32:20.357 --> 00:32:22.192
You will not allow?

470
00:32:22.276 --> 00:32:23.610
Molly. this isn't the '60s.

471
00:32:23.694 --> 00:32:26.047
and NASA's not the same place it was
when Deke was around.

472
00:32:26.071 --> 00:32:27.865
And your blind refusal...

473
00:32:31.910 --> 00:32:34.162
- That's not what I meant.
- I know what you fucking meant.

474
00:32:34.246 --> 00:32:37.976
I'm done debating this with you.
My job is to assign all the flight crews.

475
00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:41.461
including who will command
the Mars '96 mission.

476
00:32:41.545 --> 00:32:42.522
So I did my job.

477
00:32:42.546 --> 00:32:45.340
- You should not have done that.
- Well. what's done is done.

478
00:32:48.468 --> 00:32:50.572
No. what's done is now undone.

479
00:32:50.596 --> 00:32:52.306
You're fired. Molly.

480
00:32:55.350 --> 00:32:57.227
You wouldn't dare.

481
00:32:57.728 --> 00:33:00.355
I would. And I did.

482
00:33:01.273 --> 00:33:04.234
Leave your badge at the desk
on your way out.

483
00:33:21.919 --> 00:33:23.128
Admiral Baldwin's here.

484
00:33:24.087 --> 00:33:25.690
- Hey. Ed.
- Hey.

485
00:33:25.714 --> 00:33:26.691
Have a seat.

486
00:33:26.715 --> 00:33:30.010
Did you. uh. get a chance
to look at my crew wish list yet?

487
00:33:31.720 --> 00:33:34.056
Ed. we need to talk.

488
00:33:35.557 --> 00:33:37.577
I know. It... It's about Kelly. right?

489
00:33:37.601 --> 00:33:40.562
Look. I get it. But it's not just
'cause she's my daughter.

490
00:33:40.646 --> 00:33:43.815
- She's abundantly qualified...
- Ed. it's not about that.

491
00:33:45.943 --> 00:33:46.944
Okay.

492
00:33:52.574 --> 00:33:55.077
You're not going to command
the Mars mission.

493
00:33:56.620 --> 00:33:58.580
What?

494
00:33:58.664 --> 00:34:00.457
- No. M... Molly...
- Jumped.

495
00:34:01.667 --> 00:34:06.088
Jumped the gun.
Danielle Poole is the agency's choice.

496
00:34:13.804 --> 00:34:15.597
I-I don't understand.

497
00:34:15.681 --> 00:34:18.141
Ed. you're a great commander.
No one questions that.

498
00:34:18.225 --> 00:34:22.789
But Danielle's got a broader skill set
in planetary science and...

499
00:34:22.813 --> 00:34:24.106
This is bullshit.

500
00:34:26.440 --> 00:34:28.025
Jerking me around like this.

501
00:34:28.819 --> 00:34:31.822
I know. And I apologize.

502
00:34:33.197 --> 00:34:37.637
Wait. what the hell happened?
Why isn't Molly telling me this?

503
00:34:37.661 --> 00:34:40.330
Because it's my call.

504
00:34:41.081 --> 00:34:43.166
And Molly no longer works here.

505
00:34:45.085 --> 00:34:47.254
- As of when?
- As of today.

506
00:34:47.880 --> 00:34:49.590
So who's her replacement?

507
00:34:49.672 --> 00:34:51.925
Going forward.
flight crews will be determined

508
00:34:52.009 --> 00:34:55.094
by mission parameters
as defined by a selection committee.

509
00:34:57.890 --> 00:34:59.516
By a selection committee.

510
00:35:03.395 --> 00:35:05.314
By a selection committee.

511
00:35:06.273 --> 00:35:10.777
So the weenies and the white coats
are finally calling all the shots.

512
00:35:10.861 --> 00:35:13.673
I know this new system will take
some adjustment.

513
00:35:13.697 --> 00:35:15.866
Adjustment! Hell.

514
00:35:16.783 --> 00:35:19.262
The whole reason Deke built this system
was so we know

515
00:35:19.286 --> 00:35:24.208
that the guy making the call
has had his ass on the line just like us.

516
00:35:27.294 --> 00:35:30.506
But now it's just a bunch
of pencil-pushing sycophants.

517
00:35:31.590 --> 00:35:34.510
Bravo. Margo.
I hope you're proud of yourself.

518
00:35:46.605 --> 00:35:48.273
- No way.
- Look at him go!

519
00:35:48.357 --> 00:35:50.442
Oh!

520
00:35:50.526 --> 00:35:52.587
- He's crushing him.
- There it is!

521
00:35:52.611 --> 00:35:55.215
- Off to a strong start.
- There it is. All right.

522
00:35:55.239 --> 00:35:57.717
- Yo. Bombshell's gonna crush it.
- Come on. I wouldn't put my money on him.

523
00:35:57.741 --> 00:35:58.825
- He's gonna crush it.
- Look!

524
00:35:58.909 --> 00:36:00.595
Oh. look. He's crushing him.

525
00:36:00.619 --> 00:36:03.056
- He's crushing him. He's crushing him.
- Come on.

526
00:36:03.080 --> 00:36:05.165
- Oh. oh!
- Oh. he got him up in the air!

527
00:36:05.249 --> 00:36:06.834
Oh!

528
00:36:07.459 --> 00:36:10.170
Oh. man.

529
00:36:12.381 --> 00:36:13.382
Oh!

530
00:36:14.132 --> 00:36:16.611
<i>Oh. this hurts to just watch this.</i>

531
00:36:16.635 --> 00:36:18.011
- <i>Bombshell being destroyed.</i>
- Hello?

532
00:36:18.095 --> 00:36:19.429
Man.

533
00:36:20.013 --> 00:36:22.200
- That's horrible.
- Hey. Margo.

534
00:36:22.224 --> 00:36:23.559
Hey. Yeah.

535
00:36:24.434 --> 00:36:27.729
<i>Let the bot battle begin. and
here comes Bombshell with that package...</i>

536
00:36:30.983 --> 00:36:32.109
You're kidding me.

537
00:36:32.985 --> 00:36:35.070
Wh... What happened to Ed?

538
00:36:36.613 --> 00:36:37.841
Why?

539
00:36:37.865 --> 00:36:40.927
- Oh. my God. Margo. I'm...
- I am so excited.

540
00:36:40.951 --> 00:36:44.121
And you are not gonna regret this.
Yeah? I promise.

541
00:36:46.081 --> 00:36:48.500
Yeah. See you tomorrow.

542
00:36:51.753 --> 00:36:52.880
Oh. my God.

543
00:36:54.464 --> 00:36:56.216
Oh. my.

544
00:37:22.910 --> 00:37:27.015
I never thought she'd do it.
I guess times really have changed.

545
00:37:27.039 --> 00:37:30.459
This is not the agency we signed up for.
That's for damn sure.

546
00:37:32.628 --> 00:37:34.481
I'm just glad Deke's not alive to see it.

547
00:37:34.505 --> 00:37:38.175
Hmm. To Deke. Buzz.

548
00:37:39.051 --> 00:37:41.678
To you and me. a dying breed.

549
00:37:46.934 --> 00:37:47.935
Mmm.

550
00:37:48.685 --> 00:37:50.145
You want this back?

551
00:37:50.229 --> 00:37:52.856
Pretty sure my short game is
as good as it's going to get.

552
00:37:53.732 --> 00:37:55.692
Probably get some good money
for it down at the Outpost.

553
00:37:55.776 --> 00:37:58.820
It's an authentic astronaut souvenir.

554
00:38:01.573 --> 00:38:03.825
The Outpost.

555
00:38:03.909 --> 00:38:06.411
There's another great institution
gone to hell.

556
00:38:10.123 --> 00:38:13.836
Yeah. Just like the two of us.

557
00:38:58.964 --> 00:39:01.925
Rosales. come on.
Let's get you checked in.

558
00:39:03.927 --> 00:39:05.262
Okay. Rin. Let's go.

559
00:39:43.133 --> 00:39:44.801
- Thank you.
- Have a good day.

560
00:39:45.594 --> 00:39:47.804
Uh. scotch on the rocks. Thanks.

561
00:39:58.106 --> 00:39:59.107
Hi. Bob.

562
00:39:59.191 --> 00:40:02.337
I don't even feel like
saying that in here anymore.

563
00:40:02.361 --> 00:40:04.214
It feels... feels wrong.

564
00:40:08.033 --> 00:40:10.911
Anyways. congratulations.

565
00:40:12.579 --> 00:40:14.474
First person on Mars.

566
00:40:14.498 --> 00:40:17.751
Ed. this is not how
I wanted things to go down.

567
00:40:17.835 --> 00:40:19.002
You know that.

568
00:40:19.086 --> 00:40:20.170
I'm sorry.

569
00:40:20.254 --> 00:40:22.798
You didn't do anything. NASA did.

570
00:40:23.715 --> 00:40:25.551
Bean counters have taken over.

571
00:40:26.635 --> 00:40:27.803
Gordo called this.

572
00:40:28.470 --> 00:40:31.807
Saw this bullshit coming way back
when we were on Jamestown.

573
00:40:33.016 --> 00:40:34.327
There's no room for pioneers.

574
00:40:34.351 --> 00:40:36.186
Who's the birthday girl?

575
00:40:37.688 --> 00:40:39.082
Three. two. one.

576
00:40:39.106 --> 00:40:40.566
Liftoff!

577
00:40:41.275 --> 00:40:42.651
Happy birthday!

578
00:40:46.989 --> 00:40:49.408
Liftoff.

579
00:40:50.826 --> 00:40:56.915
Well. in four years. you'll be
140 million miles away from this bullshit.

580
00:40:56.999 --> 00:41:00.127
I'll probably be over there in that corner
signing souvenirs.

581
00:41:00.878 --> 00:41:04.464
Not likely. Nobody here will have any idea
who the hell you are.

582
00:41:04.548 --> 00:41:07.509
Mmm. Probably not.

583
00:41:12.306 --> 00:41:14.808
I guess I'll always wonder

584
00:41:14.892 --> 00:41:17.769
why I didn't land Apollo 10
when I had the chance.

585
00:41:20.564 --> 00:41:22.584
But at least that was my own doing.

586
00:41:22.608 --> 00:41:28.030
This. you know...
Just having it taken away from...

587
00:41:29.031 --> 00:41:30.949
And for...

588
00:41:34.369 --> 00:41:35.245
For what?

589
00:41:37.247 --> 00:41:38.248
Dani.

590
00:41:40.918 --> 00:41:42.503
I know what you're capable of.

591
00:41:43.754 --> 00:41:48.568
I trained you. I've flown with you.
Hell. I gave you your first command.

592
00:41:48.592 --> 00:41:49.694
But?

593
00:41:49.718 --> 00:41:54.014
But we both know
there are other factors at play here.

594
00:41:56.683 --> 00:41:57.851
Other factors?

595
00:42:00.187 --> 00:42:01.688
Like what. Ed?

596
00:42:01.772 --> 00:42:03.690
Come on. Dani.

597
00:42:05.067 --> 00:42:08.570
You're a damn fine astronaut.
Nobody's disputing that.

598
00:42:08.654 --> 00:42:11.925
But if this were a level playing field.

599
00:42:11.949 --> 00:42:14.576
I'd be commanding this mission.
and you know it.

600
00:42:23.627 --> 00:42:25.128
I don't even know what to say.

601
00:42:27.631 --> 00:42:32.261
I've heard crap like that my whole life.
but I never thought I'd hear it from you.

602
00:42:34.721 --> 00:42:36.265
Dani.

603
00:42:43.772 --> 00:42:45.691
Hey. Dani.

604
00:43:05.377 --> 00:43:06.420
Come on.

605
00:43:23.270 --> 00:43:25.689
What's wrong?

606
00:43:26.565 --> 00:43:28.358
<i>I lost my watch.</i>

607
00:43:29.735 --> 00:43:34.591
Oh. I'm sure it's around somewhere.
You'll find it. You always do.

608
00:43:34.615 --> 00:43:36.658
Is. uh... Is Javi there?

609
00:43:36.742 --> 00:43:38.118
<i>Oh.</i> sí. sí. <i>Uh...</i>

610
00:43:38.952 --> 00:43:41.139
Javi!

611
00:43:43.874 --> 00:43:45.083
<i>Javi!</i>

612
00:43:45.167 --> 00:43:46.478
You and Vic getting along?

613
00:43:46.502 --> 00:43:50.422
<i>Um... I get along with him.</i>

614
00:43:50.506 --> 00:43:52.317
<i>He... He doesn't get along with me.</i>

615
00:43:52.341 --> 00:43:55.802
<i>Papá</i>. please try to make it work
between you two. okay?

616
00:43:55.886 --> 00:43:56.905
- I can't...
- <i>Hi. Mommy.</i>

617
00:43:56.929 --> 00:43:59.908
Hi. baby. Do you know where I am?

618
00:43:59.932 --> 00:44:01.993
<i>I'm on the moon.</i>

619
00:44:02.017 --> 00:44:05.205
- <i>Uh-huh.</i>
- I'm on the Jamestown Base.

620
00:44:05.229 --> 00:44:07.207
You've seen it on TV. right?

621
00:44:07.231 --> 00:44:08.982
<i>I am working on</i> Sojourner 1<i>.</i>

622
00:44:09.066 --> 00:44:13.880
which is this big ship that'll take people
from the moon to Mars four years from now.

623
00:44:13.904 --> 00:44:17.300
Your <i>mamá</i> is working on the engines
that will take it there.

624
00:44:17.324 --> 00:44:20.220
<i>Oh. Oh.</i>

625
00:44:22.955 --> 00:44:26.166
He's watching the <i>DuckTales</i>.

626
00:44:32.464 --> 00:44:35.092
<i>Papá</i>. it's real.

627
00:44:35.759 --> 00:44:40.073
I'm actually here.
I'm on the moon.

628
00:44:40.097 --> 00:44:41.306
<i>Can you believe it?</i>

629
00:44:41.390 --> 00:44:46.538
No. Your mother would be so proud.

630
00:44:46.562 --> 00:44:48.313
<i>So proud of you.</i>

631
00:44:56.530 --> 00:44:58.198
Yeah. I wish she was here too.

632
00:44:59.867 --> 00:45:01.845
<i>A-Aleida.
I need to find my watch. I'm sorry.</i>

633
00:45:01.869 --> 00:45:03.847
<i>I-I... I have to make dinner at 6:00.</i>

634
00:45:03.871 --> 00:45:05.455
I need to find my watch.

635
00:45:05.539 --> 00:45:06.999
<i>Have you looked on the bedside table?</i>

636
00:45:07.583 --> 00:45:10.210
- <i>Maybe someone stole it.</i>
- No one stole your watch.

637
00:45:12.004 --> 00:45:13.505
<i>Papá?</i>

638
00:45:14.381 --> 00:45:15.465
<i>Papá?</i>

639
00:45:25.225 --> 00:45:29.771
<i>And now a man you know well.
your governor. Jim Bragg.</i>

640
00:45:29.855 --> 00:45:32.834
<i>Although unexpected.</i>

641
00:45:32.858 --> 00:45:36.171
<i>Senator Wilson's choice of
Governor James Bragg as her running mate</i>

642
00:45:36.195 --> 00:45:40.258
<i>is considered by many political analysts
to be a savvy political move.</i>

643
00:45:40.282 --> 00:45:42.242
<i>Governor Bragg's strong...</i>

644
00:45:43.410 --> 00:45:48.248
<i>...and consistent conservative positions are
expected to solidify the evangelical vote.</i>

645
00:45:54.379 --> 00:45:55.380
Ed?

646
00:45:56.381 --> 00:45:59.486
Jesus. what the hell are you doing here?

647
00:45:59.510 --> 00:46:01.595
Goddamn toy car.

648
00:46:02.304 --> 00:46:03.847
Hey. are you all right?

649
00:46:05.807 --> 00:46:07.202
Well. you're bleeding.

650
00:46:07.226 --> 00:46:09.061
Goddamn rosebushes.

651
00:46:09.770 --> 00:46:14.441
Okay. Well. I guess we're gonna go in
and get you cleaned up.

652
00:46:15.067 --> 00:46:16.443
Goddamn boot.

653
00:46:36.547 --> 00:46:40.884
I'll be pushing 70 by the time
the next Mars mission launches.

654
00:46:42.177 --> 00:46:44.429
You think
they'll be bringing on a geriatric?

655
00:46:44.513 --> 00:46:46.098
Fuck no.

656
00:46:48.809 --> 00:46:49.935
So what's left?

657
00:46:51.186 --> 00:46:52.896
More milk runs to the moon?

658
00:46:54.273 --> 00:46:56.400
M-Maytag repairs in low Earth orbit?

659
00:46:57.401 --> 00:47:00.237
I'm closer to the end
than the beginning. Kar.

660
00:47:02.072 --> 00:47:04.825
It's not how I wanted to go out.

661
00:47:13.917 --> 00:47:16.146
I know. You hate it when I mope.

662
00:47:18.505 --> 00:47:20.048
How you holding up with everything?

663
00:47:21.508 --> 00:47:24.261
Heard you sold the company.

664
00:47:25.721 --> 00:47:26.930
Yep.

665
00:47:30.184 --> 00:47:33.955
Yeah? I-I mean.
that's not the reaction you'd expect

666
00:47:33.979 --> 00:47:36.815
from someone with millions of dollars
in their bank account.

667
00:47:37.816 --> 00:47:42.070
Polaris was supposed to be
this whole new chapter.

668
00:47:43.572 --> 00:47:44.907
Now it's just gone.

669
00:47:51.663 --> 00:47:53.892
I guess this is the...

670
00:47:53.916 --> 00:47:57.604
...big. beautiful tomorrow
we used to always dream of.

671
00:47:57.628 --> 00:47:58.837
Mmm.

672
00:47:58.921 --> 00:48:01.089
A lot less shiny
than I thought it would be.

673
00:48:02.799 --> 00:48:03.800
Yeah.

674
00:48:04.718 --> 00:48:06.428
You ever wonder...

675
00:48:07.763 --> 00:48:08.740
What?

676
00:48:08.764 --> 00:48:13.769
...what our lives would have been like
if we hadn't met that day?

677
00:48:17.773 --> 00:48:21.401
You mean if I hadn't have run into
a burst pipe on Penfield Avenue

678
00:48:21.485 --> 00:48:23.713
and taken Friar
on the way to school instead

679
00:48:23.737 --> 00:48:28.033
and run into you in a vacant lot
setting off bottle rockets?

680
00:48:28.617 --> 00:48:31.245
I guess you have thought about it.

681
00:48:32.412 --> 00:48:33.747
Only once or twice.

682
00:48:36.750 --> 00:48:37.835
Who knows?

683
00:48:39.253 --> 00:48:41.755
Maybe I would have done something
completely different.

684
00:48:41.839 --> 00:48:44.383
Come on. Ed.

685
00:48:44.925 --> 00:48:48.387
You not be an astronaut? Yeah. right.

686
00:48:50.514 --> 00:48:51.974
Civil engineer. maybe.

687
00:48:54.017 --> 00:48:57.813
You know. my first year
at Annapolis. I thought about it.

688
00:48:58.605 --> 00:48:59.690
About leaving the Academy.

689
00:49:01.567 --> 00:49:03.336
- Really?
- Yeah.

690
00:49:03.360 --> 00:49:06.488
It was pure hell. I missed home.

691
00:49:06.572 --> 00:49:09.074
I missed you.

692
00:49:15.205 --> 00:49:16.540
So why didn't you?

693
00:49:18.667 --> 00:49:21.879
- I wanted to fly.
- Mm-hmm.

694
00:49:22.504 --> 00:49:26.592
And I... didn't wanna let you down.

695
00:49:31.763 --> 00:49:34.433
I guess I did that anyway. Too many times.

696
00:49:44.902 --> 00:49:47.154
So why in the world a civil engineer. Ed?

697
00:49:51.491 --> 00:49:55.329
Be nice to build something that lasts.

698
00:49:56.914 --> 00:50:00.685
Like a bridge. Or a dam.

699
00:50:02.669 --> 00:50:05.672
I mean. I've been flying
for. what. 40 years...

700
00:50:07.007 --> 00:50:09.092
- Yeah.
- ...and what do I have to show for it?

701
00:50:09.176 --> 00:50:12.638
Handful of medals. Mission patches.

702
00:50:13.138 --> 00:50:15.349
Faded photographs in newspapers.

703
00:50:18.060 --> 00:50:22.231
Enough to fill a shoebox in the closet.

704
00:50:50.175 --> 00:50:53.071
Hi. Uh. I'm Karen Baldwin.
here to see Dev.

705
00:50:53.095 --> 00:50:54.429
- All right.
- Okay.

706
00:50:57.516 --> 00:50:59.327
Is this your first time at Helios?

707
00:50:59.351 --> 00:51:01.019
Yes. it is.

708
00:51:01.103 --> 00:51:03.772
If you get a chance after your meeting.
check out Building 2.

709
00:51:03.856 --> 00:51:05.691
That's where we assemble our rockets.

710
00:51:06.191 --> 00:51:09.087
We got this 3D printer
to make our engine parts.

711
00:51:09.111 --> 00:51:13.216
Dramatically reduces our production costs
and does wonders for quality control.

712
00:51:13.240 --> 00:51:14.741
Okay.

713
00:51:16.201 --> 00:51:17.494
Thank you. Renee.

714
00:51:18.829 --> 00:51:19.997
Karen.

715
00:51:20.581 --> 00:51:23.208
Is this your office?

716
00:51:23.959 --> 00:51:25.520
- Is something wrong?
- No. no. no.

717
00:51:25.544 --> 00:51:29.590
I... I don't know. I just...
I thought you would have an office.

718
00:51:30.174 --> 00:51:32.259
We don't have
a hierarchical structure here.

719
00:51:32.759 --> 00:51:34.386
We're a collective. Remember?

720
00:51:38.140 --> 00:51:39.826
So what'd you want to see me about?

721
00:51:39.850 --> 00:51:44.813
Well. I was wondering if you had chosen
a commander for your mission to Mars.

722
00:51:45.397 --> 00:51:47.274
- Not yet.
- How come?

723
00:51:47.941 --> 00:51:51.820
After our modifications to your hotel.
the spacecraft will be mostly automated.

724
00:51:52.487 --> 00:51:54.239
The crew will largely be caretakers.

725
00:51:55.199 --> 00:51:58.428
Okay. But you still need a strong leader.

726
00:51:58.452 --> 00:51:59.596
Indeed.

727
00:51:59.620 --> 00:52:02.581
Thankfully. we have a lot
of qualified astronauts here at Helios.

728
00:52:03.290 --> 00:52:06.543
Hey. Do you want a yerba maté?

729
00:52:08.045 --> 00:52:09.046
Sure.

730
00:52:11.924 --> 00:52:17.095
Look. a Helium-3 truck driver
isn't really going to cut it.

731
00:52:17.179 --> 00:52:20.307
You're going up against NASA
and the Soviets.

732
00:52:20.849 --> 00:52:22.702
I mean. if you intend to tell the world

733
00:52:22.726 --> 00:52:27.105
you're going to slap an outboard motor
on my hotel and drive it to Mars.

734
00:52:27.189 --> 00:52:29.441
Wall Street's gonna laugh at you.

735
00:52:29.525 --> 00:52:31.920
You need somebody
who can lend you credibility.

736
00:52:31.944 --> 00:52:35.155
somebody with a long. legendary résumé

737
00:52:35.239 --> 00:52:38.575
who can galvanize
the public's imagination.

738
00:52:38.659 --> 00:52:41.787
They'll be galvanized when we land on Mars
before anybody else.

739
00:52:44.122 --> 00:52:45.332
If you land.

740
00:52:46.500 --> 00:52:48.460
What happens
when something goes wrong out there?

741
00:52:48.544 --> 00:52:51.880
Communication between there and Earth
can take up to eight minutes.

742
00:52:51.964 --> 00:52:54.484
and you need somebody on the scene
who can improvise.

743
00:52:54.508 --> 00:52:55.884
adapt and overcome.

744
00:52:56.510 --> 00:52:58.178
Somebody who isn't gonna
buckle under pressure

745
00:52:58.262 --> 00:52:59.823
but. in fact. thrives under it.

746
00:52:59.847 --> 00:53:02.182
Why do I get the feeling
you got somebody in mind?

747
00:53:04.518 --> 00:53:05.561
My ex-husband.

748
00:53:08.522 --> 00:53:10.649
I assumed NASA was selecting him
for their mission.

749
00:53:12.818 --> 00:53:15.863
Ed's unhappy with the way
things are being run over there.

750
00:53:16.905 --> 00:53:17.906
Of course he is.

751
00:53:18.490 --> 00:53:20.158
He's looking for his next challenge.

752
00:53:20.784 --> 00:53:23.287
And I think he might just love
what you're trying to do here.

753
00:53:24.830 --> 00:53:26.123
You mean what we are doing here?

754
00:53:29.376 --> 00:53:32.129
Hey. everybody. Bring it in.

755
00:53:49.938 --> 00:53:51.398
This is Karen Baldwin.

756
00:53:52.191 --> 00:53:55.110
And she just pitched me
a very interesting idea.

757
00:53:55.736 --> 00:53:59.549
What do you guys think about having
Ed Baldwin command our expedition to Mars?

758
00:53:59.573 --> 00:54:01.885
- Love it.
- That'd be radical.

759
00:54:01.909 --> 00:54:02.826
Yeah.

760
00:54:02.910 --> 00:54:04.846
Like having Babe Ruth
on your baseball team.

761
00:54:06.038 --> 00:54:08.123
Uh. Babe Ruth's dead.

762
00:54:08.207 --> 00:54:11.311
I'm pretty sure Ed Baldwin's
not too far behind.

763
00:54:11.335 --> 00:54:12.604
No offense.

764
00:54:13.921 --> 00:54:15.857
But he's got the right experience.

765
00:54:15.881 --> 00:54:17.984
and no one's ever flown a ship like this.

766
00:54:18.008 --> 00:54:19.092
Exactly.

767
00:54:19.176 --> 00:54:21.863
And he's probably stuck in his ways
like everyone else at NASA.

768
00:54:21.887 --> 00:54:25.432
This is about leadership.
The mission's over two years long.

769
00:54:25.516 --> 00:54:27.202
We need somebody like him.

770
00:54:27.226 --> 00:54:30.938
I hear what you're saying. but maybe
we should give somebody new a chance.

771
00:54:31.897 --> 00:54:32.940
I think it's a no-brainer.

772
00:54:33.649 --> 00:54:35.150
He should have been first to the moon.

773
00:54:35.234 --> 00:54:36.652
Let's make him first to Mars.

774
00:54:40.113 --> 00:54:41.657
Interesting points of view.

775
00:54:42.574 --> 00:54:44.368
All in favor. raise your hands.

776
00:54:56.713 --> 00:55:00.467
Okay. I will talk to Ed.

777
00:55:13.605 --> 00:55:15.899
- Karen.
- Yes?

778
00:55:16.525 --> 00:55:18.277
- I forgot one thing.
- Yeah?

779
00:55:21.196 --> 00:55:24.157
Come work for me.
You practically already are.

780
00:55:24.241 --> 00:55:27.160
What? You're offering me a job?

781
00:55:28.620 --> 00:55:29.705
Uh. doing what?

782
00:55:31.498 --> 00:55:32.583
Whatever you want.

783
00:55:34.209 --> 00:55:35.395
What does that mean?

784
00:55:35.419 --> 00:55:37.796
There's no official titles here.

785
00:55:37.880 --> 00:55:39.464
- no real hierarchy.
- Mm-hmm.

786
00:55:39.548 --> 00:55:42.217
So start with doing
what you did for Polaris.

787
00:55:43.093 --> 00:55:44.404
You recruited the best astronauts.

788
00:55:44.428 --> 00:55:46.346
engineers and flight controllers
in the business.

789
00:55:46.430 --> 00:55:47.574
You know where the talent lies.

790
00:55:47.598 --> 00:55:50.434
and you... you know how to hook 'em.

791
00:55:54.438 --> 00:55:59.193
I appreciate the offer. Dev. I do.
But I... I don't think so.

792
00:56:00.360 --> 00:56:01.820
Karen.

793
00:56:03.322 --> 00:56:06.909
So you rolled the dice on a wild idea
and it didn't pan out.

794
00:56:09.203 --> 00:56:10.287
So what?

795
00:56:11.914 --> 00:56:13.832
Show me somebody who never failed.

796
00:56:14.333 --> 00:56:16.752
and I will show you somebody
who never took risks.

797
00:56:18.837 --> 00:56:21.191
I can't do it again.
I'm... I'm really sorry.

798
00:56:21.215 --> 00:56:24.510
What better tribute to Sam's life

799
00:56:25.719 --> 00:56:30.766
than to help me take what
the two of you built to the Red Planet.

800
00:56:42.903 --> 00:56:46.156
Aleida Rosales worked out
the NERVA glitch in the lunar shipyard.

801
00:56:46.240 --> 00:56:48.176
so we have that back on the timeline.

802
00:56:48.200 --> 00:56:50.702
But we can't afford
another slip like that.

803
00:56:51.328 --> 00:56:53.014
Ninety-six sounds pretty far away.

804
00:56:53.038 --> 00:56:56.351
but those four years are gonna be gone
before we can draw a breath.

805
00:56:56.375 --> 00:56:58.418
Well. let's get started on the crew then.

806
00:56:58.502 --> 00:57:00.128
The sooner we get them in the loop.

807
00:57:00.212 --> 00:57:03.066
the faster we can get the hardware
and mission design up to speed.

808
00:57:03.090 --> 00:57:08.095
I have Ed's crew wish list here.
He'd already reached out to them.

809
00:57:10.597 --> 00:57:13.642
He wanted his daughter on the trip?

810
00:57:16.728 --> 00:57:18.331
If you want her or any of them.
just say so.

811
00:57:18.355 --> 00:57:22.442
If not. you'll have to give them
the bad news.

812
00:57:22.526 --> 00:57:25.612
Well. I already got some ideas
about who I want in my right seat.

813
00:57:25.696 --> 00:57:26.697
Hmm.

814
00:57:27.197 --> 00:57:29.342
Now. as you know. he's a damn good pilot.

815
00:57:29.366 --> 00:57:32.929
and his knowledge of advanced avionics
will come in real handy up there.

816
00:57:32.953 --> 00:57:35.372
Excuse me.

817
00:57:37.165 --> 00:57:38.166
What is it?

818
00:57:38.250 --> 00:57:40.085
There's something on the news
you may wanna see.

819
00:57:41.128 --> 00:57:42.254
Thanks. Nuri.

820
00:57:46.592 --> 00:57:48.510
<i>Soloflex. Simple...</i>

821
00:57:48.594 --> 00:57:50.345
<i>Flame-broiled perfection.</i>

822
00:57:51.722 --> 00:57:53.932
<i>And I'd like to welcome
the co-founder of Polaris.</i>

823
00:57:54.016 --> 00:57:56.286
<i>Karen Baldwin. to the Helios family.</i>

824
00:57:58.937 --> 00:58:01.481
So now he wants to be
the next Conrad Hilton?

825
00:58:01.565 --> 00:58:05.527
<i>Some say private citizens
have no business in space travel.</i>

826
00:58:05.611 --> 00:58:08.298
<i>Well. I emphatically disagree.</i>

827
00:58:08.322 --> 00:58:11.426
The first hot-air balloon
to carry a human being aloft

828
00:58:11.450 --> 00:58:13.994
was designed by the Montgolfier brothers.

829
00:58:15.287 --> 00:58:20.042
The first powered aircraft was built
by a pair of bicycle makers.

830
00:58:20.626 --> 00:58:21.710
Wilbur and Orville Wright.

831
00:58:23.128 --> 00:58:26.316
Charles Lindbergh made
the first solo flight across the Atlantic

832
00:58:26.340 --> 00:58:28.550
in a plane built by a private company.

833
00:58:29.176 --> 00:58:30.445
And Robert Goddard.

834
00:58:30.469 --> 00:58:33.680
he built the first liquid-fueled rocket
that streaked into the heavens

835
00:58:34.556 --> 00:58:36.910
on his little farm
in Auburn. Massachusetts.

836
00:58:36.934 --> 00:58:41.104
We acquired Polaris to enable us
to embark on a bold new expedition.

837
00:58:41.188 --> 00:58:42.981
taking us where no man has gone before.

838
00:58:43.065 --> 00:58:46.568
By adding our groundbreaking
new Osprey-methane engines to it.

839
00:58:47.361 --> 00:58:49.863
<i>we will propel
this one-of-a-kind spacecraft</i>

840
00:58:49.947 --> 00:58:53.951
<i>out of Earth orbit on an epic journey
of exploration...</i>

841
00:58:55.994 --> 00:58:56.995
<i>to Mars.</i>

842
00:59:02.501 --> 00:59:04.044
<i>Ladies and gentlemen of the world.</i>

843
00:59:05.212 --> 00:59:06.880
<i>I am thrilled to present to you...</i>

844
00:59:08.382 --> 00:59:09.609
<i>Phoenix</i>.

845
00:59:12.928 --> 00:59:16.431
We will establish a free enterprise zone
on the Red Planet

846
00:59:16.515 --> 00:59:20.245
<i>so that innovation
and economic development will thrive.</i>

847
00:59:20.269 --> 00:59:25.500
<i>building a new colony.
a new society benefiting all people.</i>

848
00:59:25.524 --> 00:59:27.317
<i>But don't take my word for it.</i>

849
00:59:27.401 --> 00:59:29.820
Take the word of the man
who will command our mission.

850
00:59:31.280 --> 00:59:35.093
A living legend
whose experience reaches back

851
00:59:35.117 --> 00:59:37.619
to the earliest days of space exploration.

852
00:59:38.203 --> 00:59:40.038
<i>The man who commanded
the first lunar base.</i>

853
00:59:40.122 --> 00:59:43.518
<i>staying alone when his crew
had to return to Earth.</i>

854
00:59:43.542 --> 00:59:47.921
<i>The first commander to operate
a nuclear engine in space.</i>

855
00:59:49.840 --> 00:59:51.234
Ed Baldwin.

856
01:00:00.851 --> 01:00:02.227
- What the...
- ...hell?

857
01:00:04.855 --> 01:00:06.106
<i>Thanks. Dev.</i>

858
01:00:09.026 --> 01:00:12.905
Ed Baldwin won't have to wait four years
to lead our expedition.

859
01:00:13.405 --> 01:00:17.367
<i>We'll be going
in the next Mars launch window. 1994.</i>

860
01:00:17.451 --> 01:00:21.306
<i>a full two years before NASA
or the Soviet Union.</i>

861
01:00:21.330 --> 01:00:25.083
The future belongs to all of us.

862
01:00:50.692 --> 01:00:52.694
Way to go. Ed.

863
01:00:53.195 --> 01:00:55.822
Stick it to the bastards.
